stle, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton Castle, Jórvík, England","Skelton, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton, Jórvík, England"},"nl":{"about 1264–1332":"circa 1264–1332","1270–1349":"1270–1349","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","1291–Female":"1291–Overleden","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1332":"1332","1210":"1210","1264":"1264","about 1289":"circa 1289","about 1264":"circa 1264","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England","Skelton, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1264–1332":"about 1264–1332","1270–1349":"1270–1349","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1291–Female":"1291–Deceased","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1332":"1332","1210":"1210","1264":"1264","about 1289":"about 1289","about 1264":"about 1264","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England","Skelton, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Whitney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Whitney in Herefordshire, the etymology of which is uncertain. The second element is Old English <i>ēg</i> ‘island, piece of higher ground in a low-lying area’; the first appears to be <i>hwītan</i>, which is either the genitive singular of an Old English byname <i>Hwīta</i> (meaning ‘white’), or the weak dative case (originally used after a preposition and article) of the adjective <i>hwīt</i> ‘white’. The name may also derive from Whitney (now Whitney Wood) in Stevenage (Hertfordshire), probably named from Old English <i>hwītan</i> ‘white’ + <i>(ge)hæge</i> ‘enclosure’.","History: John Whitney came from London, England, to Watertown, MA, in 1635, and had numerous prominent descendents."],"variants":[{"name":"Witney","meanings":["English: habitational name from Witney in Oxfordshire, which for centuries was a centre of the wool trade, famous in particular for the manufacture of blankets. The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Witta</i> (genitive <i>Wittan</i>) + Old English <i>ēg</i>, <i>īeg</i> ‘island’. There may have been some confusion with   Whitney  ."]},{"name":"Widney","meanings":["English: variant of   Whitney  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":26,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":51,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":64,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Whitney was born about 1264, in Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England. He married Female Whitney about 1289, in Skelton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1332, in Skelton, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 69."},"et":{"about 1264–1332":"umbes 1264–1332","1270–1349":"1270–1349","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","1291–Female":"1291–Surnud","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1332":"1332","1210":"1210","1264":"1264","about 1289":"umbes 1289","about 1264":"umbes 1264","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England","Skelton, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1264–1332":"noin 1264–1332","1270–1349":"1270–1349","1210–Female":"1210–Kuollut","1291–Female":"1291–Kuollut","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1332":"1332","1210":"1210","1264":"1264","about 1289":"noin 1289","about 1264":"noin 1264","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England","Skelton, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1264–1332":"environ 1264–1332","1270–1349":"1270–1349","1210–Female":"1210–Décédée","1291–Female":"1291–Décédée","1264–1332":"1264–1332","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1332":"1332","1210":"1210","1264":"1264","about 1289":"environ 1289","about 1264":"environ 1264","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Skelton Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton Castle, Everwyck, Angleterre","Skelton, Yorkshire, England":"Skelton, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William Whitney est né environ 1264, à Skelton Castle, Everwyck, Angleterre. Il a épousé Female Whitney